Java dependencies → mvn install or gradle build
Node.js dependencies → npm install (Node Package Manager)
Python dependencies → pip install (pip install requests)
OS packages → yum install or apt-get install
------------------------------------------

Node.js
----------

FROM node:20-alpine

WORKDIR /app

COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install

COPY . .
# source      = . → your local machine current folder
#                   everything in it
# destination = . → current WORKDIR inside container
#                   which is /app

# Same as: COPY . /app         # explicit version ✅

EXPOSE 3000

CMD ["npm", "start"]

--------
npm install

It installs all Node.js dependencies listed in your package.json file.

So if your package.json has:

{
  "dependencies": {
    "express": "^4.18.0",
    "mongoose": "^8.0.0"
  }
}
2 COPY = Docker layer caching trick ✅

COPY package.json first:
  dependencies cached ✅
  npm install skipped ✅
  saves time on every build ✅

COPY . . after:
  source code copied last
  only rebuilds when
  code changes ✅

✅ index.js / app.js (your main server file)
✅ routes/, controllers/, models/ (your app folders)
✅ .env (if not excluded via .dockerignore — careful, often you WANT to exclude this)
✅ package.json, package-lock.json (again — harmless, already copied, just re-copied)
❌ node_modules from your LOCAL machine — this should be excluded via .dockerignore,
